name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF004273%2F1"><gtr:id>A0240B65-9467-4E90-8CF4-9AE54DFE3C6E</gtr:id><gtr:title>The role of learning in imitation and body representation</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F004273/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Imitation is an important ability in the highly social environment in which we dwell. It allows us to learn new skills from others. Although a great deal is known about the functions of imitation, little is known about its supporting mechanisms. One hypothesis suggests that imitation mechanisms develop through learning, such that links form between visual and motor representations of action whenever these representations are active at the same time.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This project will aim to explore this hypothesis by investigating whether imitation effects can be modulated through training. It will initially investigate effects behaviourally, looking at reaction times to perform imitative and non-imitative actions, before and after training where non-imitative actions are executed. It is predicted that, before training, participants will be faster to execute imitative than non-imitative actions. After training, if imitation mechanisms develop through experience, this advantage should reduce, or even reverse. This project will subsequently investigate neurological correlates of these effects, with event-related potentials.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research will have crucial implications for businesses who wish to employ effective imitation training techniques. Furthermore, this research will have implications for patients where imitation mechanisms are impaired, such as those with autism spectrum disorders and apraxia.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>67199</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/F004273/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>